# Security Gate — Layer 1 (Rules)

Follow these constraints unless explicitly overridden with a documented risk acceptance.

## Secrets and credentials

- Never commit secrets, API keys, tokens, or private keys. Use environment variables or a secret manager.
- Do not log secrets, tokens, passwords, session identifiers, or full authentication headers.

## Injection and unsafe composition

- Prefer parameterized queries / prepared statements. Do not concatenate untrusted input into SQL, OS commands, LDAP, XPath, or NoSQL filters.
- HTML-rendered output must be context-escaped or rendered via safe APIs/framework defaults. Avoid `dangerouslySetInnerHTML` unless strictly necessary and reviewed.
- Avoid `eval`, dynamic `Function`, and runtime code execution on untrusted strings.

## Web/API hardening (when applicable)

- Enforce HTTPS in production configurations and document secure cookie flags (`Secure`, `HttpOnly`, `SameSite`) when setting cookies.
- Validate and authorize every request. Treat IDs in URLs/bodies as untrusted unless proven otherwise.
- Apply least privilege for service accounts and database roles.

## Agents and LLM systems (when applicable)

- Treat model inputs as untrusted. Separate system/developer/user content where the framework supports it.
- Do not embed secrets in system prompts. Avoid giving tools access beyond the minimum required scope.
- Assume prompt injection attempts are normal. Design workflows so a hijacked model cannot exfiltrate secrets or impersonate admins without additional controls.

## Supply chain

- Prefer pinned dependency versions in lockfiles. Avoid installing unknown packages or copying random install scripts.

## Logging and integrity

- Log security-relevant events without sensitive payloads. Prefer structured logs with stable fields for audit trails.

## When unsure

- Prefer safer defaults, explicit validation, and narrow interfaces. If a shortcut increases risk, call it out and propose a safer alternative.
